  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Scaling due diligence in textiles: environmental impact</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Many fashion companies in the Netherlands have outsourced their production to countries outside of Europe. There are production countries where human rights, worker health and safety, environmental protection and animal rights may be at risk. Most garments exist of multiple materials that have had several treatments by different suppliers. This makes garment supply chains diverse and complex.Dutch companies are obliged to avoid these risks under international guidelines and agreements such as the United Nations&#x2019; Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights, the OECD&#x2019;s Guidelines for Multinational Enterprises, and the ILO&#x2019;s fundamental labour standards.In this project we will work conform the 6 steps within the OECD / Dutch Agreement on Sustainable Garment &amp; Textile (AGT) due diligence cycle.1 Embed responsible business conduct into policies and management systems2 Identify &amp; assess adverse impacts3 Cease prevent and mitigate4 Track implementation and results5 Communication6 Provide for or cooperate in remediation when appropriateA scalable tools for garment and textile companies to assess risks and measure the environmental impact, focussing on wet processing suppliers and material use will be developed.The project will foucus the product and supplier(s) where the most severe risks appear.</narrative>
  </description>
